al backgrounds during their crucial first years of resettlement in the United States and Canada and asylum in Germany. All three countries offer a legal solution to displacement, while simultaneously minoritizing newcomers through policies that fail to recognize their histories, aspirations, and personhood. The United States stands out for its emphasis on “self-sufficiency” that integrates refugees into American poverty, which, by design, is populated by people of color and marked by stagnation. Gowayed argues that refugee human capital is less an attribute of newcomers, than a product of the same racist welfare systems that have long shaped the contours of national belonging.Centering the human experience of displacement, Refuge shines needed light on how countries structure the potential of people, new arrivals or otherwise, within their borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aRefugeeszSyriaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAdult.  aAntifeminism.  aArabic pop music.  aAsylum seeker.  aAtheism.  aAvailability.  aBashar al-Assad.  aBasic income.  aBill Clinton.  aBoarding school.  aCairo University.  aCanadians.  aCession.  aClothing.  aCombatant.  aConscription.  aCredential.  aCredit card.  aDental hygienist.  aDivine grace.  aEarned income tax credit.  aEast Germany.  aEconomics.  aEmployment.  aEvening.  aExploration.  aFacebook.  aFamily reunification.  aFinancial transaction.  aForklift.  aFunding.  aHauptschule.  aHijab.  aHousehold.  aHuman capital.  aIdlib.  aImmigration law.  aImmigration.  aIncome.  aIndividualism.  aInteraction.  aInterrogation.  aIslam.  aJustin Trudeau.  aKibbeh.  aLaptop.  aLeitkultur.  aLinen.  aLong Term.  aManuscript.  aMohamed Bouazizi.  aMu